@NODE Einführung "Introduction"
@{b} Introduction @{ub}

  I have written this little program to get an overview over all the fonts
  I have installed for Wordworth. The name of the font is displayed in
  the standard font format, so you can read the names of symbol fonts, too.



@ENDNODE
@node ANFORDERUNGEN "Requirements"
@{b}Requirements@{ub}

This program needs of course:

    Wordworth 6 (5 should be possible, but not tested)

    ARexx: The program "RexxMast" should be in the drawer "WBStartup"

@endnode

@node INSTALLATION "Installation"
@{b}Installation@{ub}

   Copy "FontList.rexx" in the drawer WWRexx. Then you go to "ARexx-Macro" in
   the Wordworth-menu "Extras", click on "new" and then on "FontList.rexx", of course.
   Now you can start it by another double-click.
   Click @{"here" link Ablauf} to see how the program works.

@endnode

@node ABLAUF "Running"
@{b}Running the program@{ub}

  First, the script searches for the path where the list of fonts is located.
  Then you can choose a name for the Fontlist. After that, Wordworth loads a list of all fonts
  and works a little bit with it. I'm afraid you have to click on "OK" once, when WW proudly
  presents a requester saying "xxx replaced". It is not possible to leave this requester out.
  (Confer @{"Problems" link Probleme}.)
  When you have installed more than 80 fonts, you should follow the advise to split the list in
  several parts, as it might be that Wordworth makes @{"trouble" link Probleme} otherwise.

  The names of the fonts are always displayed in the font you have chosen as "Normal". So you
  are able to read the names of Symbol Fonts, too.

  Do you want to have another text than this boring "ABC", or do you want to have another
  fontsize? See @{"Configuration" link Konfiguration}.


@endnode
@node KONFIGURATION "Configuration"
@{b}Configuration@{ub}
  You can alter both font size and the text displayed. Do it as follows:

  1. Load FontList.rexx with a text editor, e.g. GoldEd. Also Wordworth is possible,
     but make sure that you save it as ASCII afterwards.

  2. Look for the following lines:
@{FG shine}     //* --------------------------------*/
     /*  Change Fontsize and Text here: */

     FontSize="15pt"
     Text1="ABCDEFG HIJKLMNOP QRSTUVW XYZÄÖÜ"
     Text2="abcdefg hijklmnop qrstuvw xyzäöüß"
     Text3="12345 67890 !§$%& /()=?"

     /* -----------------------------*/  @{FG text}
     Here you can alter whatever you want. But the "" around text and fontsize are absolutely
     necessary! This means that you cannot include a " in the text itself. Sorry. If you know
     ARexx quite well, you should be able to include it, but it's a bit complicated. If you want
     to have less than 3 lines of text, you have to write e.g. Text3="". This will produce a blank
     line in the fontlist, which you can remove afterwards by replacing ¶¶ through ¶ in Wordworth
     (¶ is Left-Alt-p)
     You should also make a space after some letters, as Wordworth reacts a bit @{"queer" link Probleme} if it
     doesn't know how to hyphenate a word.

  3. Save it again (As ASCII, if you have used a Word processor.)


@endnode
@node PROBLEME "Problems"
@{b}Problems@{ub}

  I'm afraid it is not so easy to write ARexx-programs for Wordworth. There are things you just can't
  do with Wordworth and ARexx. No wonder there are not very many publications.

  These are the problems:

  1. It seems that Wordworth is not able to have more than ca. 80 fonts at once. Sometimes yes,
     sometimes no. That's not a problem of lack of memory.
     This is why my program recommends you to split the list in several parts. If you don't
     do that, the worst thing can be that you get the Requester: "Not able to open Font xxx".

  2. Unexplainable crashes: It was reported to me that Wordworth always crashed with a special
     font. It seems that WW does not like all letters of all fonts. In such case, try the
     following:
     - Choose the font that makes trouble
     - Type ABC etc, just as in the fontlist. (Ä, Ö, Ü are reached by pressing Left-Alt-k before
       pressing a, o, u. ß is Left-Alt-s.)
     - If WW crashes at a certain letter, you have found the troublemaker.
     - @{"Change" link Konfiguration} the example text, leaving out this letter.
     - If this doesn't help, write to @{"me" link Copyright}.

  3. If WW doesn't know how to hyphenate a word, it hyphenates it after each letter sometimes.
     Like that:
     W-
     o-
     r-
     d-
     usw.
     This looks a bit queer, doesn't it? That's why I have inserted a blank space here and there.
     Well, you can @{"change" link Konfiguration} that of course, if you want.

  4. In case of other mistakes, contact @{"me" link Copyright}.

In case of a bug in the program, you can stop it very simply by pressing the close-button of the
window. ARexx won't find the Wordworth-port, tell you that it can't work any more, and stop it.
Another possibility is to type HI in a shell. That doesn't mean "Hallo there", but "Halt Interrupt"
which lets all ARexx-programs stop.


@endnode
